.87,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.89,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n            \"feedback\": \"Closely parallels P1 but replaces Fe oxyhydroxide with Ni\u2070/H\u2082 catalysis. Well-supported by Kaur et al. (2024) reporting ~17% alanine yield over Ni nanoparticles at pH 7-8, 22\u00b0C, 24h, 5 bar H\u2082. The mild conditions (room temperature, neutral pH) are notable and prebiotically relevant. Same upstream CO\u2082-to-pyruvate bottleneck as P1.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_022\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify meteoritic or native metal sources for Ni\u2070 to strengthen geochemical plausibility\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.88, \"rxn_002\": 0.87, \"rxn_003\": 0.75, \"rxn_004\": 0.72, \"rxn_007\": 0.88, \"rxn_008\": 0.87, \"rxn_022\": 0.60},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.86,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.76,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.81,\n            \"feedback\": \"Incorporates the nitrogen-shuttle concept from Schlikker et al. (2024/2025) showing 34% pyruvate-to-alanine conversion with pyridoxal at pH 11, 80\u00b0C on Ni\u2070. The pyridoxal-pyridoxamine cycling is elegant and well-supported. However, the pathway requires pyridoxal to already be available\u2014its prebiotic synthesis (rxn_019) is speculative. The combined CO\u2082-to-pyruvate + cofactor requirements make this the most demanding pathway.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_022\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Explicitly include pyridoxal genesis steps in pathway definition\", \"Consider whether pyridoxal could be replaced by simpler pyridine derivatives\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_009\": 0.84, \"rxn_011\": 0.92, \"rxn_012\": 0.90, \"rxn_022\": 0.60},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.86,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.79,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n            \"feedback\": \"Good hydrothermal-to-surface transition. Diederich et al. (2023) support acetaldehyde generation from C\u2082H\u2082/CO on NiS, and the subsequent Strecker steps are classical and well-established. The 180 \u00b5M / 0.02% yield reported by Diederich is low but measurable. Requires HCN source (from rxn_010 or another route), which is not explicitly included in the 4 steps but is available from the network. Compact and chemically sound.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_022\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Explicitly note HCN source dependency\", \"Consider whether acetaldehyde stability during transport from hydrothermal to surface is plausible\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_010\": 0.88, \"rxn_011\": 0.92, \"rxn_012\": 0.90, \"rxn_022\": 0.60},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.89,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n            \"feedback\": \"The most classically supported pathway, directly descending from Miller (1953). Spark discharge generates HCN, acetaldehyde, and NH\u2083 in situ, followed by well-established Strecker chemistry. Johnson et al. (2008) reanalysis shows alanine/glycine molar ratios up to 0.9-1.4 in some configurations. Simple, robust, and well-documented. Environmental progression is entirely Surface, lacking Hydrothermal contribution, which slightly reduces environmental interconnection score but strengthens internal coherence.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_022\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Could note that discharge configuration strongly affects alanine yield (Johnson et al. 2008)\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_010\": 0.88, \"rxn_013\": 0.82, \"rxn_014\": 0.84, \"rxn_015\": 0.83, \"rxn_022\": 0.60},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n            \"feedback\": \"Well-aligned with Green et al. (2023, JACS) showing efficient N-formylaminonitrile formation in formamide systems with staged heating. The formamide intermediate (rxn_013) provides a stabilization mechanism for nitrile chemistry. The literature emphasizes that aminonitrile-first routes may primarily populate precursors rather than free amino acids, making the hydrolysis step (rxn_015) the environmental bottleneck\u2014this is correctly captured. The requirement for formamide-rich microenvironments is geochemically debatable.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_022\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Discuss geochemical plausibility of sustained formamide-rich microenvironments\", \"Note that staged heating is important for selectivity (Green et al.)\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_016\": 0.78, \"rxn_022\": 0.60},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.76,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.72,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.70,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.74,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.73,\n            \"feedback\": \"Supported by Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) showing 23 amino acids from H\u2082S-enriched spark discharge with racemic alanine. However, representing this as a single reaction is an oversimplification that obscures the complex radical chemistry and aqueous processing involved. The pathway is too compressed to provide mechanistic insight. It functions best as a 'known endpoint' validation rather than a detailed synthesis route.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Decompose into at least gas-phase radical steps and aqueous capture/processing\", \"Include intermediate species to improve mechanistic transparency\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.88, \"rxn_002\": 0.87, \"rxn_003\": 0.75, \"rxn_004\": 0.72, \"rxn_021\": 0.85, \"rxn_011\": 0.92, \"rxn_012\": 0.90, \"rxn_022\": 0.60},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.92,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.78,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n            \"feedback\": \"Creatively bridges hydrothermal and surface environments by generating pyruvate hydrothermally, decarboxylating to acetaldehyde at the surface, then using Strecker chemistry. The thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate (rxn_021) is well-established chemistry. This pathway provides the best environmental interconnection narrative and demonstrates how hydrothermal products can feed surface chemistry. The 7-step length is justified by the cross-environment logic. Same upstream CO\u2082-to-pyruvate issues as P1/P2.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_022\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify temperature/conditions for pyruvate decarboxylation at the surface\", \"Note that acetaldehyde volatility aids the transport between environments\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pa