FT studies (Asthagiri & Hazen, 2007) show <1 kcal/mol selectivity for alanine on chiral calcite. The network correctly identifies this as a module rather than a single well-defined reaction. Multiple amplification cycles or coupling to crystallization dynamics would be needed. As a standalone pathway it is weak, but as a network module it serves a necessary function.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_022\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Consider decomposing into specific chiral selection mechanisms (calcite adsorption, CPL, crystallization)\", \"Include Soai-type amplification or deracemization cycling concept\", \"Address whether alanine's lack of \u03b1-methyl group makes it harder to enantioenrich than \u03b1-methylamino acids (per Cronin & Pizzarello)\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is an exceptionally well-designed synthesis network that demonstrates thorough engagement with the prebiotic chemistry literature. The network's major strengths are: (1) Correct identification of the two major carbon-skeleton entry points\u2014acetaldehyde-based Strecker chemistry and pyruvate-based reductive amination\u2014as the organizing axes, directly matching the literature synthesis. (2) Excellent literature alignment with 8+ key experimental studies (Barge 2019, Kaur 2024, Schlikker 2024, Diederich 2023, Green 2023, Parker 2011, Miller 1953, Dherbassy 2023), with specific quantitative benchmarks properly reflected. (3) Strong hub molecule selection (pyruvate, acetaldehyde, HCN, aminonitrile, DL-alanine) matching the literature's identification of key branch points. (4) Good environmental flow from Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical, with minerals properly specified. (5) Honest treatment of the chiral selection bottleneck. The main weaknesses are: (a) The CO\u2082-to-pyruvate hydrothermal steps (rxn_003, rxn_004) via Woo