s of aminonitrile to alanine is plausible but can be slow at neutral pH (literature notes this as a bottleneck). Environmental progression Surface\u2192Biochemical is clean. Only 4 steps, making it one of the most parsimonious routes.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_021\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify conditions/catalysts that could accelerate aminonitrile hydrolysis prebiotically\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.55\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.83,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n      \"feedback\": \"Formamide-stabilized variant supported by Green et al. 2023 JACS showing N-formyl-Ala-CN formation. The HCN\u2192formamide step (rxn_015) is described as 'UV photolysis' which is somewhat nonstandard\u2014HCN hydration to formamide is more conventional. The stabilization concept is valuable and addresses the hydrolysis timing bottleneck identified in the literature. Adds useful complexity to the simpler P4 route.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify the HCN\u2192formamide mechanism: hydration vs photolysis\", \"Consider whether formamide-rich microenvironments are geochemically sustainable\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.55\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.87,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.73,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n      \"feedback\