0.90,\n        \"rxn_020\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.55\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.92,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n      \"feedback\": \"Impressive proto-biochemical pathway spanning all three environments: Hydrothermal (pyruvate synthesis), Surface (glycine via formaldehyde Strecker + UV photoreduction on TiO\u2082), Biochemical (metal-pyridoxal transamination). Supported by Dherbassy et al. 2023 showing Fe\u00b3\u207a-pyridoxal is ~90\u00d7 faster than pyridoxal alone. However, same pyridoxal sourcing issue as P3, and the pathway requires convergence of three independently generated molecules (pyruvate, glycine, pyridoxal). The 7-step length adds cumulative yield concerns.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Address pyridoxal prebiotic origin\", \"Discuss concentration/compartmentalization requirements for three-component convergence\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.55\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.86,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n      \"feedback\": \"Fully hydrothermal vent pathway using sulfide minerals, well-aligned with Novikov & Copley 2013's pyruvate reactivity landscape. The literature emphasizes that yields vary 'strikingly' across different minerals, adding realism but also uncertainty. Same upstream CO\u2082 fixation concerns. Provides diversity in mineral catalysts compared to P1/P2.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify which sulfide minerals are most favorable for alanine selectivity based on Novikov & Copley data\", \"Note the competition with lactate and propionate formation\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.55\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.93,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.73,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n      \"feedback\": \"The most network-aware pathway, creating the cross-environment feedback loop (pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 Strecker). This demonstrates the interconnected nature of the network\u2014hydrothermal carbon fixation generates pyruvate, which can either directly undergo reductive amination OR decarboxylate to acetaldehyde for surface Strecker chemistry. The decarboxylation step is thermally facile. This pathway beautifully illustrates the convergence of metabolism-first and Strecker-first paradigms. The Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical flow is well-justified.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_021\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Discuss whether this feedback loop could be self-sustaining\", \"Consider kinetic competition between direct reductive amination vs decarboxylation\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is an exceptionally well-designed prebiotic synthesis network for L-alanine that demonstrates deep engagement with the literature. The dual-hub strategy around pyruvate (metabolism-first) and acetaldehyde (Strecker-first) accurately reflects the field's consensus on alanine's major prebiotic entry points. Nearly every reaction maps onto specific experimental li